social_posts.post_text: Ever wonder why ppl who exercise are always so positive and motivational ? It’s no coincidence. Neuroscience tells us that through natural selection and evolution, out biology has been wired to trigger reward centers when we move in away that makes us happy (and in a way that one’s kept us alive). Our body releases endorphins and serotonin to make you feel optimistic and lessen pain. The norepinephrine allows you to be more focused, and it boosts our memory too. The dopamine you receive during exercise keeps you motivated throughout the day. and oxytocin make you feel connected to your community and want to help others.  When we work on ourselves we make this world a little better by being the best version of ourselves and giving others the permission to do the same. We all know that exercise is good for the body, but it’s high time we start giving it credit for our mental and emotional health as well!!

All levels Handbalance Tuesdays and Thursdays at 4:30p @theyogadojo 
.
if you can warrior three you can do this class.  the back, shoulder and leg extension required for warrior three is the basis of the conditioning techniques that we do for the first 30 minutes of class.  Also we dive into a more nuanced understanding of the hand placement, finger and wrist strength and specific coordination drills for inverting safely and comfortably. “it is an about intensity, it’s about consistency”
.
 Handbalance is like learning a new language, we just want to learn a word or two each class and overtime it will develop into our balance fluency. Hope to see you there.

I wish I had Known this sooner. 
.
My twin brother took me to the Italian circus for our 30th birthday we saw handbalance act performed on 10 foot canes,  I fell in love immediately, I knew I was going to dedicate a substantial part of my life to learning this art form. But, I had no idea how to practice, or what alignment I should be aiming for, or how to steer clear of injury.  needless to say I got each one of those components wrong.  I caused injury from poor alignment, poor instruction and I wasted Countless hours kicking to a wall without knowing how to use it properly.  it wasn’t until I found the assistance of a highly qualified coach that I started to understand the fundamental principles, and how they were there to asure there were no injuries along the way. I learned that each skill was a progressive step that was working towards developing an overall understanding of Handbalance and how far it can be taken when the fundamentals are practiced consistently. Improper instruction can lead to partial definitions and explanations without the real reason behind the instruction, and some cases cause injuries or poor movement patterns. what I learned from my coaches in the early years of my training is what I practice with them still to this day.  the fundamental truths of alignment, conditioning, injury prevention and confidence in balance. But those fundamentals are always given through the instruction of tremendous experience knowing why we practice the way we do. It is why I am so passionate about giving quality instruction in those areas, and why I’ve dedicated over 10 years of my life to learning how to teach others. My goal is now to teach my students the ability to build on fundamentals in a progressive fashion to accomplish whatever their personal movement goals may be.  If you are looking for a guide to take the guesswork out of Handbalance I am here for you Tuesdays and Thursdays 4:30p @theyogadojo 
.

I haven’t been practicing hand balance as much as I’m used to. I’ve been more focused on dedicating my time to @theta_wellness_rva and @theyogadojo . I’ve been more focused on teaching and learning (reading 2 books a week) and providing as informative and supportive a class as I can. And I’ve been enjoying alternative movements like climbing, calisthenics, and Pilates (first official class was this week) and I feel pretty good about that. I think our lives have seasons and we are always balancing the things we love to do and feel called to pursue.  So here’s to maintaining systems of health weve committed to while still exploring the world and trying out new things in new environments. And here’s to all the people out there sharing there love of health and wellness in all the different ways.

Core Calisthenics tonight at 7:15p. 
.
This class is designed to improve , strength coordination and range of motion. The strength that is developed is typically the strength of endurance.  the muscles will be able to respond to a longer duration of effort,  improving our energy production and efficiency of movement. The class improves our range of motion to increase our active flexibility and so joints can rest in a more efficient position. allowing for the therapy of better posture, which creates more space for respiratory function. strong posture equals strong breathing, strong breathing equals strength of health. 
.
If you want life span and health span to be connected this class is for you
.
Wednesday 7:15p @theyogadojo

When I first got into yoga 11 years ago I mostly just practiced in my room. when I discovered arm balances a year into my practice, I Immediately fell in love. I searched for a studios to learn more about arm balances but couldn’t find any. After driving all over the east coast with no luck, I finally found one in San Francisco called @astayogasf And after taking a leap of faith, and some stars lining up in my favor I traveled there to learn and study from them.  I brought back everything I learned from the rocket sequence and study of arm balances and inversions. After a few years of teaching in Richmond VA, I teamed up with my best friend and now biz partner @flowwithlo and we created a space dedicated to personal exploration of individual potential and Rocket Yoga. The good news is you don’t need to travel to San Francisco to learn these methods.  We are bringing our instructor @stevepyka here to share in a immersive rocket continuing Ed training at our studio @theyogadojo July 19-23. 
.
If you are on the West Coast, I can’t recommend enough visiting @astayogasf 
.
I put the sign-up link for more info in my bio if you want to take it to the next level with us. I can honestly say the rocket training was one of my peak experiences of life I remember it as if it were yesterday. It was nothing short of life changing.

The way you do anything, is the way you do everything. 
.
 which is to say, I get obsessed over things ! when I first started handstands, my  big goal was a 30 second hold.  I thought that would be pretty cool.  I had no idea how far my personality traits were going to take me. I don’t know if we get to select the things we are interested in, or become obsessed over. but I’d like to think I’m choosing healthier habits with things that produce positive results in my life and Community.  I remember when I was younger those same personality traits were used towards non-productive monotonous partying,  that didn’t serve me or anyone else. Recognizing my personality trait I try to leverage it as a sort of way out of the mud of partying,  becoming “obsessed“ with health and overall wellness. It’s interesting how the environment and intention can refocus the very same personality traits that can be self-destructive and in another environment  can be wellness affirming. I think intention , environment and community can make all the difference in the world!! someone once said to me that you are the culmination of the five people you’re closest to, I hope that’s true. Becuse of @theyogadojo and yoga in general I have so many amazing, inspiring people all around me.  I think that may be the secret to it all, find people and Community who can inspire you to be the best version of yourself, and see how far you can take it.

Traveling by yourself can be a strange experience.  on one hand, we’re always traveling by ourselves, no matter who we are with.  The internal environment is out stage for every experience.  Even sharing our experiences with someone else, is played out in our internal environment. all feelings and emotions that we will ever have will be created from our internal environment and played back to us in that vary same areas of sensation. we all want to feel connected and belonging to a group or to our friends, but even the emotion of belonging is one that is experienced exclusively by the self. So take that trip with or without someone, we require it to grow and to be reintroduced to who we are in this moment. The human mind shrivels without odysseys on the horizon and expands with dreams of travel. I’ll be returning back to Richmond tomorrow and am looking forward to my classes @theyogadojo before we head up to west VA for a weekend retreat  @casaompotomac 
.
Looking forward to seeing you soon and sharing our stories of personal travel we call life 
.

Interest will always dictate effort. Of all the students I have had the privilege of working with over the years the ones who are most interested in Handbalance, yoga, self improvement and learning in general are the ones who always show up with the most effort and focus,  and end up progressing the most because of it. 

.
find what you are most interested in and make sure your efforts coincide with your level of interest. 
.
We’re all busy people, it’s a natural state of the human experience.  But make sure you’re busy with the priorities and things you have identified as primary goals.  you could be busy all day watching TV and won’t move the needle towards your goals an inch.  or you could fill your day being busy with things you care deeply about, that will get you closer to your goals as well as produce a life of meaning and purpose. 
.
if you would like to practice the rituals of self-love we call discipline, I teach Tuesday and Thursday 4:30 Handbalance and 6PM Vinyasa as well as Wednesday evening core Calisthenics at 7:15p and Friday 12noon Calisthenics flow @theyogadojo right next to @theta_wellness_rva 
.
